/SCC/XXOMMENTARY/XX. The historical origins of the love poems that comprise /ITShir
Hashirim/XX (The Song of Songs) is unknown. Were they simple shepherd
love poetry, as they present themselves, or did they have a cultic setting
in the distant pre-Israelite past, as some have suggested? The Kabbalists
prescribed the recitation of the Song of Songs at /ITKabbalat Shabbat/XX. They
saw it as a love poem between the blessed Holy One and the /ITSheh/±inah/XX, or
the male and female elements within divinity. Only in the union of these
two can divine blessing flow into the world, giving us the enjoyment of
Shabbat peace./PR

/SC/XXA.G./XX/PR

/PR

/SCN/XXOTE/XX. The translator, hearing a play on words in Hebrew, uses the spice
name "balsamum" because of its likeness in sound to "Solomon." King
Solomon is the reputed author of /ITShir Hashirim/XX.    /SC/XXJ.R./XX/PR

